ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) â€” Some 80,000 at-home COVID-19 tests are beginning to be handed out by city officials in areas of Albuquerque determined to need them the most.The supplies are from the federal government and the distribution has started in areas of high social vulnerability. The Barelas Senior Center was one of the first stops.Each person who wanted the at-home tests were getting four kits, which is eight COVID-19 tests total.Albuquerque has 25 locations designated for distribution, including community centers, libraries, and local organizations. City officials said that there eventually will be test instructions in 12 different languages.Michelle Melendez, director of Office of Equity for the City of Albuquerque, told KOB-TV that testing is going to be one of the best strategies to stop transmission of the virus.